    "5dc43db6-6071-46a1-bcd3-87149f927c4d": {
      "type": "loop-article-richtext",
      "blocks": {
        "bbe5d3fe-7467-4ad2-8dba-0a60a333b6cf": {
          "type": "heading",
          "settings": {
            "heading": "Avoid caffeine and sugar",
            "heading_size": "h2"
          }
        },
        "template--15759467872452__5dc43db6-6071-46a1-bcd3-87149f927c4d-16669657084aaae098-0": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>It may seem obvious, but it’s surprisingly easy to disrupt your sleep and your ability to fall asleep by consuming caffeine or sugar too late in the day. Caffeine can be particularly problematic as it has a half-life of around five hours in the average person. So if you drink a coffee at 5 pm, you’ll still have around half the caffeine in your body by 10 pm.<\/p><p>To avoid or reduce the negative impacts of sugar and caffeine on sleep, try to limit intake to the mornings and early afternoons.<\/p>"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "bbe5d3fe-7467-4ad2-8dba-0a60a333b6cf",
        "template--15759467872452__5dc43db6-6071-46a1-bcd3-87149f927c4d-16669657084aaae098-0"
